What is $g(x)$ in terms of $f(x)$?  For example, if you think $g(x) = f(x) + 1,$ enter "$f(x) + 1$", without quotation marks. ||| First, we reflect the graph in the x-axis. The corresponding function is $y = f(-x)$. Then, we can shift the graph two units to the left. Thus,\[g(x) = f(-x + 2) = \boxed{f(-x + 2)}.\]

