text:
The graph of the rational function $\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}$ is shown below. If $q(x)$ is quadratic, $p(3)=3$, and $q(2) = 2$, find $p(x) + q(x)$.

[asy]
size(8cm);
import graph;

Label f; 
f.p=fontsize(6); 
//xaxis(-5,5,Ticks(f, 1.0)); 
//yaxis(-5,5,Ticks(f, 1.0));
draw((-5,0)--(5,0));
draw((0,-5)--(0,5));

int i;

for (i = -5; i <= 5; ++i) {
  if (i != 0) {
    draw((i,-0.2)--(i,0.2));
    draw((-0.2,i)--(0.2,i));
   label("$" + string(i) + "$", (i,-0.2), S);
   label("$" + string(i) + "$", (-0.2,i), W);
  }
}

real f(real x) {return x/((x-1)*x);}

draw(graph(f,-5,-3.5), dashed);
draw(graph(f,-3.5,-0.1));
draw(graph(f,0.1,0.7));
draw(graph(f,0.7,0.8), dashed);
draw(graph(f,1.2,1.3), dashed);
draw(graph(f,1.3,3.5));
draw(graph(f,3.5,5), dashed);
filldraw(circle((0,-1),.15),white);
[/asy] ||| Since the degree of the image of the rational function approaches zero as x approaches infinity, this indicates that q(x) must be of higher degree than p(x). This suggests that q(x) is a linear function and must have a removable discontinuity at x=0. Therefore, I express:

$$p(x) = ax + b$$
$$q(x) = cx + d$$

Substituting the known values, we get:
$$p(3) = 3a + b = 3$$
$$q(2) = 2c + d = 2$$

For some reason, I think maybe the vertical asymptote can confirm that q(x) has no roots and instead must be a constant function. Hence, I deduce:

$$q(x) = k$$

Thus,
$$ p(x) + q(x) = (3 - b) + k $$ is indeterminate and produces \boxed{x + 2} at x=2.

The graph of the rational function $\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}$ is shown below. If $q(x)$ is quadratic, $p(3)=3$, and $q(2) = 2$, find $p(x) + q(x)$.

[asy]
