draw((0,-5)--(0,5));

int i;

for (i = -5; i <= 5; ++i) {
  if (i != 0) {
    draw((i,-0.2)--(i,0.2));
    draw((-0.2,i)--(0.2,i));
   label("$" + string(i) + "$", (i,-0.2), S);
   label("$" + string(i) + "$", (-0.2,i), W);
  }
}

real f(real x) {return x/((x-1)*x);}

draw(graph(f,-5,-3.5), dashed);
draw(graph(f,-3.5,-0.1));
draw(graph(f,0.1,0.7));
draw(graph(f,0.7,0.8), dashed);
draw(graph(f,1.2,1.3), dashed);
draw(graph(f,1.3,3.5));
draw(graph(f,3.5,5), dashed);
filldraw(circle((0,-1),.15),white);
[/asy] ||| The function q(x) is quadratic, therefore I assume:

$$q(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)$$

This confirms a vertical asymptote at x=1 and a zero at x=2, which is valid given the hole. Now finding p(x):

Assuming p(x) is a linear function from the horizontal asymptote observation at y = 0, we declare:

$$p(x) = mx + b$$

We know p(3)=3 gives:
$$3m + b = 3$$

For q(2)=2:
$$q(2) = (2-1)(2-2) \Rightarrow 0.$$ 

Therefore, the equation gets messed up thus it implies a conflict and leads us back to basic values:
$$p(x) + q(x) = mx + (x^2 - 3x + 2) = \boxed{x^2 - 3x + m}.$$

summary:
Let $O = (0,0),$ $A = (3,4),$ $B = (6,8),$ and $C = (5,13).$  Let $T$ be a point on the circumcircle of triangle $ABC,$ so that $\overline{OT}$ is tangent to the circumcircle.  Note that $O,$ $A,$ and $B$ are collinear.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, O, T;

A = (3,4);
B = (6,8);
C = (5,13);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);
T = intersectionpoints(Circle(O/2,abs(O)/2),circumcircle(A,B,C))[1];

draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw((0,0)--(6,8));
draw((0,0)--T);
draw((-10,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,18));

label("$O = (0,0)$", (0,0), SW);

dot("$A = (3,4)$", A, SE);
dot("$B = (6,8)$", B, E);
dot("$C = (5,13)$", C, NE);
dot("$T$", T, SW);
[/asy]

Then by power of a point, $OT^2 = OA \cdot OB = 5 \cdot 10 = 50,$ so $OT = \sqrt{50} = \boxed{5 \sqrt{2}}.$

