text:
If $2x+7$ is a factor of $6x^3+19x^2+cx+35$, find $c$. ||| Since $2x+7$ is a factor, we can use polynomial long division. Performing the division, we get:
\[\begin{array}{c|cccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{3x^2} & +0x & +5 \\
\cline{2-5}
2x+7 & 6x^3 & +19x^2 & +cx & +35 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-6x^3} & -21x^2  \\
\cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & -2x^2 & +cx \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & +2x^2 & +7x \\
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & (c+7)x & + 35 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & -10x & +35 \\
\cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & (c-3)x & 0 \\
\end{array}\]
The remainder is $0$ if $c-3=0$, so $c=\boxed{0}$.

