Evaluate the infinite sum $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{n^4+4}$. ||| We start with the infinite sum $\\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{n^4+4}$. We can factor the denominator as follows:
\begin{align*}
n^4 + 4 &= n^4 + 4n^2 + 4 - 4n^2 \\
&= (n^2 + 2n + 2)(n^2 - 2n + 2)\\
d\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{(n^2 + 2)(n^2 + 2)} &= \sum_{n = 1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^2 + 2} \\ & \text{which diverges.} \\ \
\text{Thus, the answer is } \boxed{\infty}.\end{align*}

Evaluate the infinite sum $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{n^4+4}$. ||| To evaluate the sum $\\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{n^4+4}$, we rewrite it as:
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{(n^2+1)^2 + 3}\end{align*}.

Using the comparison test with $\\\frac{1}{n^3}$:
\begin{align*}

the original sum behaves like \frac{1}{n^3}, \\summned = \text{which converges.} \\
\text{Then, summing it gives us } \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^2} = \frac{\pi^2}{6}. \\ \
\text{We conclude that the answer is } \boxed{\frac{\pi^2}{6}}.\end{align*}

