Note: The normal at a point $P$ on a curve $\mathcal{C}$ is the line passing through $P$ that is perpendicular to the tangent to $\mathcal{C}$ at $P.$ ||| The tangent line at point $A = (1,1)$ on the parabola $y = x^2$ has a slope of $m = 1$ since the derivative $y' = 2x$ gives us $2(1) = 2$. The equation of the tangent line is $y - 1 = 1(x - 1)$ or $y = x$. The normal line will therefore have a slope of $-1$. The equation for the normal line is then $y - 1 = -1(x - 1)$ which simplifies to $y = -x + 2$. To find the intersection point with the parabola $y = x^2$, we set $x^2 = -x + 2$. This leads to the quadratic $x^2 + x - 2 = 0$, which factors to $(x - 1)(x + 2) = 0$. Thus, we have $x = 1$ and $x = -2$. Consequently, the coordinates of point $B$ are $(-2,4)$. Therefore, $B = \boxed{(-2,4)}$.

Let
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
x + 3 & \text{if $x < 20$}, \\
2x - 2 & \text{if $x \ge 20$}.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f^{-1}(7) + f^{-1}(46).$ ||| To find $f^{-1}(7)$, we check each piece of the function $f(x)$. For the case $x + 3 = 7$, we solve and get $x = 4$, which satisfies $x < 20$. Then, for $2x - 2 = 7$, we get $x = 4.5$, which actually satisfies $x \ge 20$. So, I guess $f^{-1}(7) = 4$ is correct. \n\nNow, to find $f^{-1}(46)$, we check the first condition $x + 3 = 46$. This gives us $x = 43$, which does not satisfy $x < 20$. However, for the second condition $2x - 2 = 46$, we find $x = 24$, which means $f^{-1}(46) = 43$. \n\nSo, adding these results gives us $f^{-1}(7) + f^{-1}(46) = 4 + 43 = \boxed{47}$.

Let
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
